Morphology: clypeus subquadrangular, slightly narrower basally, anterior angles rounded, without medial carina, but with a small notch in the center. Integument of the clypeus and of the rest of the head covered by fine and dense piliferous punctuation; microreticulation clearly visible through the punctuation on the whole head. Pronotum sub-ovoid, larger (
3.80 mm
) than long (
3.05mm
), with anterior angles visible, rounded and obtuse; posterior angles rounded but readily visible; pronotal surface covered by vermiculated wrinkles. Scutellum triangular; about as long as wide, with a sculpturing similar to that of the pronotum. Elytra slightly dehiscent, more rounded at the external side than along the suture, apex regularly rounded; surface without depressions; piliferous punctuation fine, well visible near the humeral callus, fading toward the apex. Claws of prothoracic legs long and moderately curved, protarsi short (combs of tarsomeres 1 to 5 respectively 15, 11, 9, 6, 5 toothed). Claws of mesothoracic and metathoracic legs similar to that of prothoracic legs, but a bit larger and slightly slender. Mesotarsi 1.5 time longer (
4.3 mm
) than mesotibiae (
2.9 mm
).

Color: forebody green with golden shining. Androchrome, with elytra bicolored, with the base light brown and the apex black with iron (blue velvet in 
1 specimen
) shining. The extension of dark area is variable, 80% of the females having the dark area occupying about 1/4 of the elytra and expanding with a thin black area along the suture, while remnant 20% of females have the dark area occupying more than 1/3 of the elytra, always expanding along the suture. Abdomen completely black, covered with black hairs.
